<section id="fs-id2438007">
<title>Bernoulli’s Equation for Static Fluids</title>
<para id="import-auto-id1867940">Let us first consider the very simple situation where the fluid is static—that is, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{v rSub { size 8{1} } =v rSub { size 8{2} } =0} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Bernoulli’s equation in that case is</para>
  
    <equation id="eip-871"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>ρ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">gh</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>ρ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">gh</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P rSub { size 8{1} } +ρ ital "gh" rSub { size 8{1} } =P rSub { size 8{2} } +ρ ital "gh" rSub { size 8{2} } "."} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id1867942">We can further simplify the equation by taking <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{h rSub { size 8{2} } =0} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (we can always choose some height to be zero, just as we often have done for other situations involving the gravitational force, and take all other heights to be relative to this). In that case, we get</para><equation id="eip-477"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>ρ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mstyle><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">gh</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P rSub { size 8{2} } =P rSub { size 8{1} } +ρ ital "gh" rSub { size 8{1} } "."} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id2668144">This equation tells us that, in static fluids, pressure increases with depth. As we go from point 1 to point 2 in the fluid, the depth increases by <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{h rSub { size 8{1} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and consequently, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P rSub { size 8{2} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is greater than <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P rSub { size 8{1} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> by an amount <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>ρ</m:mi><m:mstyle><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">gh</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ρ ital "gh" rSub { size 8{1} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. In the very simplest case, 

<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P rSub { size 8{1} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is zero at the top of the fluid, and we get the familiar relationship 

<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi>ρ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mstyle><m:mrow><m:mi fontstyle="italic">gh</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P=ρ ital "gh"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. (Recall that 

<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi fontstyle="italic">ρgh</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{P=hρg} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and 

<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>Δ</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext>PE</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>g</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mgh</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{Δ"PE" rSub { size 8{g} } = ital "mgh"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) Bernoulli’s equation includes the fact that the pressure due to the weight of a fluid is 

<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>ρ</m:mi><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>gh</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ρ ital "gh"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Although we introduce Bernoulli’s equation for fluid flow, it includes much of what we studied for static fluids in the preceding chapter.</para></section>

<section id="fs-id3116723">
<title>Bernoulli’s Principle—Bernoulli’s Equation at Constant Depth</title>
<para id="import-auto-id1609382">Another important situation is one in which the fluid moves but its depth is constant—that is, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{h rSub { size 8{1} } =h rSub { size 8{2} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Under that condition, Bernoulli’s equation becomes</para><equation id="eip-663"><m:math>
